{{External media|align=right|width=300px|image1=[http://thereminfamily.narod.ru/theremin_program_cover.jpg Portrait illustrated on theremin program cover]<ref>http://thereminfamily.narod.ru/</ref>|image2=[http://www.caramoor.org/images/Lucie_Rosen_playing_theremin.jpg Lucie Rosen playing the theremin, on Caramoor Center website]}} '''Lucie Bigelow Rosen''' (born 1890<ref>{{Cite book | last = Glinsky | first = Albert | title = Theremin: Ether Music and Espionage | location = Urbana, Illinois | publisher = University of Illinois Press | year = 2000 | isbn = 0-252-02582-2 | pages=129, 161, 288 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6DHlQJcMpBQC&printsec=frontcover |ref=Glinsky }}</ref> [[Bernardsville, New Jersey]] died 27 November 1968 New York)<ref>[[#Glinsky|Glinsky]] p. 288. died in her sleep ... seventy-eight years old</ref> was a [[Theremin]] soloist known for popularising<ref>[[#Glinsky|Glinsky]] p. 161. tireless advocate</ref> the use of the instrument in the 1930s and 1940s, and founder of the [[Caramoor Center for Music and the Arts|Caramoor festival]]. {{listen |filename =Vraaggesprek met Lucie Rosen over de theremin.wav| | title = Radio interview | description = Radio interview from 1935 of [[PHOHI]] with Lucie Rosen}}
==Life== Rosen was born Lucie Bigelow Dodge in 1890, and married the lawyer and banker [[Walter Tower Rosen]] in 1914. They shared a common passion in art and culture, especially Italian, making frequent European trips and collecting works of art for their [[Caramoor Center for Music and the Arts|Caramoor]] estate that they developed from 1929 to 1939.<ref>[[#Glinsky|Glinsky]] p. 130.</ref>
By 1930 Lucie was part of a ten-person theremin ensemble rehearsing for their debut at the Carnegie Hall with [[Leon Theremin]].<ref>[[#Glinsky|Glinsky]] p. 117.</ref> Sometime afterward, the Rosens offered Theremin the use of their 37 West Fifty-fourth Street townhouse at low rent. By 1938 Leon Theremin needed money to return to Russia and, according to the Rosen's daughter Anne Stern, Walter offered him ten thousand dollars to create a new machine for Lucie together with all technical papers and rights to produce more for personal use only.<ref>[[#Glinsky|Glinsky]] p. 196.</ref>
After Walter died in 1951, Lucie expanded the musical performances they had both started in 1940 into the Caramoor festival.<ref>[[#Glinsky|Glinsky]] p. 288. fully developed Caramoor festival</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/10/19/nyregion/the-view-from-katonah-for-costume-fanciers-regal-fantasy-fashions.html|title=The View From: Katonah; For Costume Fanciers, Regal Fantasy Fashions|last=Ames|first=Lynne|date=October 19, 1997|work=New York Times|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>
==Family== Her parents were Flora Bigelow and Charles Stuart Dodge; they divorced in 1902 and Flora was given custody of Lucie and her brother [[Johnnie Dodge|John Bigelow Dodge]]. She remarried to [[Guest family#Ivor Bertie Guest, 1st Baron Wimborne|Lionel Guest]], a cousin of [[Winston Churchill]] and moved to Canada and later to London. Lucie's paternal grandfather was [[Charles C. Dodge]] who was a brigadier-general during the American Civil War and had married Maria Theresa Schieffelin, daughter of [[Bradhurst Schieffelin]]. Her great grandfather was [[William E. Dodge]] who helped found [[Phelps Dodge|Phelps Dodge & Co]] and secured the family wealth. Her maternal grandfather was [[John Bigelow]] husband of Jennie Tunis Poultney.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dodge|first1=Phyllis B.|title=Tales of the Phelps-Dodge Family|date=1987|publisher=New York Historical Society|location=New York|page=217}}</ref>
In 1913 Lucie disappeared from her mother's home in London, resulting in a much publicized search involving Scotland Yard. She was discovered six days later living in London's West End theatre district. She returned home but soon after moved to New York and married Rosen.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dodge|first1=Phyllis B.|title=Tales of the Phelps Dodge Family|date=1987|publisher=New York Historical Society|location=New York|page=217}}</ref> They had two children, Anne and Walter; he was killed in 1944 on a training mission in England whilst serving with the Royal Canadian Air Force.<ref>{{cite web|title=Caramoor History|url=http://www.caramoor.org/about/history/|website=Caramoor.org|publisher=Caramoor Center for Music & the Arts, Inc.|accessdate=18 December 2014}}</ref>
